Creating Journals
Once the promo master data is created, everything that is needed for the journals and extracts are contained in one single flattened source.

The journals are created by executing 6 stored procedures:

B2B2C_PROMO_DECOUP_GL_EXTRACT()

B2B2C_PROMO_DECOUP_AP_SUPPORTING()

B2B2C_PROMO_DECOUP_DEBIT_NOTE_EXTRACT()

B2B2C_PROMO_DECOUP_AP_JOURNAL()

B2B2C_PROMO_DECOUP_GL_JOURNAL()

B2B2C_PROMO_DECOUP_SSD_FILES()

 

Stored procedures 1-5 all follow the exact same format:

A file name and folder structure is defined (based on journal type + date)

A sql script is executed, which creates the journals and extracts in the specific format they are required, as defined by finance

Note: they do not follow a typical file structure of 1 column name and data underneath those column headers. Some files contain 2 or more column names

image-20240417-114831.png
 

This is then ordered as per finance requirements (file rows must be in a particular ordered sequence). The columns used to order the files are then dropped from the final output

The output is saved to Azure Blob Storage

storageecrpprd → b2b2c-transaction-files → Output Files

They are saved as CSV extract in an organised file structure

 

Stored procedure 6, B2B2C_PROMO_DECOUP_SSD_FILES(), differs as it contains the SSD extracts. This procedure:

A file name and folder structure base is defined

Sub-folders are then created, based on the date executed (SSD_ddmmyyyy)

A sql query is calculated to define the list of suppliers that are needed to loop through the final output, to generate a single file per supplier (the row count of this statement defines how many SSD files are created for that week)

SELECT DISTINCT SUPPLIER_NUMBER,CLAIM_NUM
FROM COL_DB.COL_DM.B2B2C_PROMO_MASTER
ORDER BY SUPPLIER_NUMBER

A for loop is executed which:

Loops through each supplier ID, as per above sql statement

Runs sql statement to retrieve data required for the extract

Orders data as per requirements by finance

Drops off the ordered value columns as not required in final output

Creates a dynamic file name based on that suppliers ID and claim ID number

CSV extract is created and saved in Azure Blob Storage, based on dynamic file path and name as defined in code

Repeats until all supplier files are created

End of Task Notification
Once all 6 stored procedures are executed, another file gets created and saved to the Azure Blob Storage. This file serves no purpose other than being a trigger used to execute the next step in the process. The CSV file contains a single row and single column (SELECT 'SUCCESSFULL' AS PROMO_DECOUPLING_STATUS).

Once done this completes the Snowflake Task.

Power Automate (Sharepoint)
Once the end of task notification is executed, this kicks start the Power Automate component of the process.

Power Automate  copies the files generated from Snowflake, from Azure Blob Storage into Sharepoint Online. It then notifies users from finance (and CC’s Data BI team) that the process is complete.

The end users of these output files are members of finance, who do not have access to Azure Blob Storage. Power Automate is used to prevent someone having to manually copy and paste the files from Blob to Sharepoint.

